Content:
Happy belated $\pi$ -day! :) Prove $$\int_{0}^{\infty} \sqrt{\frac{1}{\sqrt{e^x} } - \frac{1}{e^x}} \,\mathrm dx = \pi.$$ Here is the method I used (I am interested to see if there are any other manipulations or tricks that can be used). \begin{align}
I &= \int_{0}^{\infty} \sqrt{\frac{1}{\sqrt{e^x} } - \frac{1}{e^x}} \,\mathrm dx \\ &= \int_{0}^{\infty} \sqrt{e^{-x/2} - e^{-x}} \,\mathrm dx  \\ &= -2\int_{1}^{0} \sqrt{u - u^2}\left(\frac{1}{u}\right) \,\mathrm du \\ &= 2\int_{0}^{1} \frac{\sqrt{u - u^2}}{u} \,\mathrm du \\ &= 2\int_{0}^{1} {\sqrt{\frac{u - u^2}{u^2}}} \,\mathrm du \\ &= 2\int_{0}^{1} {\sqrt{\frac{1 - u}{u}}} \,\mathrm du \\ &= 2\int_{0}^{1}2t{\sqrt{\frac{1 - t^2}{t^2}}} \,\mathrm dt \\ &= 4\int_{0}^{1} \sqrt{1-t^2} \,\mathrm dt \\ &= 4\cdot \frac\pi4 \\ &= \pi.
\end{align} I would like to see a clever alternative solution to this one; I’m sure there are other elegant ways that I want to learn from.
